WEBVTT

00:02.350 --> 00:03.655
<i>- Previously on
"Superman & Lois"...</i>

00:03.699 --> 00:05.222
Let's just focus on what
family.

00:05.266 --> 00:06.658
- Miss?
- Sharon Powell.

00:06.702 --> 00:08.399
My son was a miner
at the Edge Facility.

00:08.443 --> 00:09.879
Morgan Edge offered him

00:09.922 --> 00:11.489
"the opportunity
of a lifetime."

00:11.533 --> 00:13.100
- Turns out, Miss Powell's son

00:13.143 --> 00:14.753
isn't the only worker
who's gone missing.

00:14.797 --> 00:15.885
<i>- How's Eliza doing?</i>

00:15.928 --> 00:17.017
- She's okay, she's okay.

00:17.060 --> 00:18.148
Maybe--maybe too okay.

00:18.192 --> 00:19.671
<i>- Tag, Tag?</i>

00:19.715 --> 00:20.672
<i>I think my heat vision,</i>

00:20.716 --> 00:22.326
<i>it affected him somehow.</i>

00:22.370 --> 00:25.199
Don't try to tell me
it wasn't my fault.

00:25.242 --> 00:26.678
<i>- Captain Luthor?</i>

00:26.722 --> 00:28.028
<i>- We need to stop Kal-El</i>

00:28.071 --> 00:29.333
<i>before he does to this world</i>

00:29.377 --> 00:31.553
what he did to mine.

00:35.992 --> 00:39.517
<i>♪</i>

00:39.561 --> 00:42.085
<i>- I've always loved Smallville
during the fall.</i>

00:47.047 --> 00:48.526
<i>♪</i>

00:48.570 --> 00:50.267
<i>The changing of seasons...</i>

00:50.311 --> 00:54.402
<i>♪</i>

00:54.445 --> 00:56.273
<i>The turning of time.</i>

00:56.317 --> 01:02.236
<i>♪</i>

01:02.279 --> 01:04.194
<i>The last warm moments</i>

01:04.238 --> 01:06.240
<i>before the cold.</i>

01:06.283 --> 01:13.551
<i>♪</i>

01:27.435 --> 01:31.003
<i>But what I loved
most of all...</i>

01:31.047 --> 01:33.919
<i>was the one weekend every year</i>

01:33.963 --> 01:35.834
<i>when everyone came together</i>

01:35.878 --> 01:38.141
<i>and sacrificed
to help those in need.</i>

01:38.185 --> 01:40.187
- Harvest Fest?

01:41.275 --> 01:45.192
- So, is that why you've been
"Supermanning" all week?

01:45.235 --> 01:46.758
So you free up some time
to go to this?

01:46.802 --> 01:49.544
- It's a tradition!
Goes all the way back to 1949

01:49.587 --> 01:51.241
when Smallville
was established.

01:51.285 --> 01:52.677
It's one of the best things
about being here.

01:52.721 --> 01:54.201
- I have been hearing
about this from your dad

01:54.244 --> 01:55.767
since we first started dating.

01:55.811 --> 01:57.726
- Bedtime stories to help you
sleep, or what?

01:59.380 --> 02:01.033
- Either way, it doesn't sound
like much of a festival.

02:01.077 --> 02:03.253
Just sounds like a whole bunch
of people selling stuff.

02:03.297 --> 02:04.863
- Not just sell.
Share!

02:04.907 --> 02:06.778
You know, whatever they can,
with anyone who needs it.

02:06.822 --> 02:09.433
- Think of it as Smallville's
version of Burning Man.

02:09.477 --> 02:10.956
- Minus the fires and BO,

02:11.000 --> 02:12.262
I hope.
- Ha, ha.

02:12.306 --> 02:13.611
Your grandmother loved it,
okay?

02:13.655 --> 02:15.091
She used to spend weeks
planning

02:15.135 --> 02:16.310
what we were gonna donate.

02:16.353 --> 02:18.268
She made lists
and spreadsheets.

02:18.312 --> 02:19.661
- Your dad learned a lot
about giving

02:19.704 --> 02:21.750
and helping people
in need from this.

02:21.793 --> 02:24.448
Your dad's not Superman just
'cause he has powers, you know.

02:24.492 --> 02:25.971
- Aw, thanks, baby.
-

02:26.015 --> 02:27.538
- I know you guys aren't sold,

02:27.582 --> 02:28.974
but when you see everyone
come together like this,

02:29.018 --> 02:30.411
the--the sense of community,

02:30.454 --> 02:32.413
it's--it's the best
of what Smallville is.

02:32.456 --> 02:33.805
- It just doesn't sound
like much of a festival.

02:33.849 --> 02:35.111
- Well, they have
all that stuff too.

02:35.155 --> 02:36.373
The food stands alone.

02:36.417 --> 02:38.158
Funnel cakes,
fried cheese curds--

02:38.201 --> 02:39.768
Ooh!
The Fishers!

02:39.811 --> 02:41.465
Every year, they have this
"Sugar Bowl" stand.

02:41.509 --> 02:43.337
They make chocolate bacon.

02:43.380 --> 02:46.035
So good!
- Uh, Eliza's vegetarian, so.

02:46.078 --> 02:47.297
- Oh.
- Hey, I'm glad

02:47.341 --> 02:48.820
she's finally able
to come visit.

02:48.864 --> 02:51.345
- Look, the Harvest Fest
is special, okay?

02:51.388 --> 02:53.999
Eliza's gonna love it,
you're gonna love it...

02:54.043 --> 02:55.392
all of you are gonna love it.

02:55.436 --> 02:57.481
<i>♪</i>

02:57.525 --> 02:59.483
Let's go! Corn, let's go!
- We're gonna love it.

02:59.527 --> 03:01.920
- What?

03:02.530 --> 03:03.835
<i>- Two essays in one night.</i>

03:03.879 --> 03:05.228
It's ridiculous.
It's, like, he can't even

03:05.272 --> 03:07.012
write himself.
- Hey, Sarah.

03:07.056 --> 03:08.231
- Hey.
- Hey.

03:08.275 --> 03:10.712
- Wow, um,
they really go all-out

03:10.755 --> 03:13.149
with this Harvest Fest
stuff, huh?

03:13.193 --> 03:15.412
- I know it's kinda hokey,
but...

03:15.456 --> 03:18.067
it has its own
kind of specialness.

03:18.110 --> 03:19.286
- You sound like my dad.

03:19.329 --> 03:21.679
- Shut up.
-

03:21.723 --> 03:23.290
- Um, you guys going tonight?

03:23.333 --> 03:25.553
- Yeah.
Actually, Eliza's coming too.

03:25.596 --> 03:28.208
- Ooh, Metropolis girl?
- Yeah.

03:28.251 --> 03:29.513
- What about you?

03:29.557 --> 03:33.343
Do you maybe wanna go together?

03:33.387 --> 03:36.694
- L--like from beginning
to end?

03:36.738 --> 03:39.741
- That is how I understand
the concept of "together."

03:39.784 --> 03:40.872
- Um, Sarah,

03:40.916 --> 03:42.396
let me just speak
for my brother here.

03:42.439 --> 03:43.919
He would love to go with you.

03:43.962 --> 03:46.748
Right?

03:46.791 --> 03:49.490
- Yeah, no, no, no, yeah.
I would love to go.

03:49.533 --> 03:51.056
- Great.
Um...

03:51.100 --> 03:52.623
we'll meet up beforehand?

03:52.667 --> 03:53.972
- For sure, yeah.
I'll text you

03:54.016 --> 03:55.235
when Eliza's coming.

03:55.278 --> 03:56.714
- Cool, okay.
Um...

03:56.758 --> 03:58.194
Awesome, well.

03:58.238 --> 03:59.239
- Oh.

03:59.282 --> 04:00.936
- Okay.

04:02.242 --> 04:03.982
- Hey, babe, what's up?

04:06.420 --> 04:08.291
What?
What are you--

04:08.335 --> 04:09.771
what are you talking about?

04:11.207 --> 04:12.730
Eliza!
Hey, hey.

04:12.774 --> 04:15.777
Eliza, can we--can we please
just talk about this?

04:16.604 --> 04:18.736
Okay.
Whatever.

04:18.780 --> 04:20.129
Yeah, bye.

04:22.262 --> 04:23.306
- That didn't sound good.

04:23.350 --> 04:25.743
- It's great.
Great...

04:26.440 --> 04:28.398
If you consider getting dumped

04:28.442 --> 04:30.400
by your girlfriend
of over a year

04:30.444 --> 04:33.011
the night you're supposed
to see her "great."

04:33.055 --> 04:34.143
- Look, man, that sucks.

04:34.186 --> 04:35.579
<i>♪</i>

04:35.623 --> 04:37.233
- All good.
Welcome to Smallville,

04:37.277 --> 04:40.802
the place where you get
dumped over the phone, right?

04:40.845 --> 04:47.896
<i>♪</i>

04:51.029 --> 04:52.117
- Hey.

04:52.161 --> 04:53.684
What are you up to?

04:53.728 --> 04:56.600
- I was thinking
we'd make this the home office

04:56.644 --> 04:58.907
of the world's
most famous journalist.

04:59.603 --> 05:01.213
- But these are all
your mom's things.

05:01.257 --> 05:02.606
- Yeah, I know, but

05:02.650 --> 05:04.304
it's what she would've wanted.

05:04.347 --> 05:05.609
And the Harvest Fest
is the perfect time

05:05.653 --> 05:07.219
to give this stuff away.

05:07.263 --> 05:08.395
- Okay.

05:08.438 --> 05:10.397
If this is really
what you want.

05:11.180 --> 05:12.181
- No, no, no!

05:12.224 --> 05:13.443
Not that.
Sorry.

05:16.664 --> 05:18.274
Hey, Chrissy.

05:18.318 --> 05:20.450
- Lois, are you coming in soon?

05:20.494 --> 05:21.669
<i>- Why, what's going on?</i>

05:21.712 --> 05:23.801
- Uh, Sharon Powell's here.

05:23.845 --> 05:24.715
- She okay?

05:24.759 --> 05:27.631
- Yeah, she's okay, actually.

05:27.675 --> 05:30.112
And so is her son.

05:30.939 --> 05:33.071
- You don't remember
what happened?

05:33.115 --> 05:34.638
- Uh, no, ma'am.

05:34.682 --> 05:36.161
I was coming through the tunnel

05:36.205 --> 05:37.815
and I was reading my paycheck.

05:37.859 --> 05:40.078
Hadn't seen a number that big
in a long time.

05:40.122 --> 05:43.125
Just wasn't paying attention,
I guess, and...

05:43.168 --> 05:44.605
hit it real good.

05:44.648 --> 05:47.172
Next thing I know, I wake up
in Stanton County.

05:47.216 --> 05:48.870
- They found him
outside a church.

05:48.913 --> 05:49.653
St. Anthony's.

05:49.697 --> 05:51.089
- They helped me remember

05:51.133 --> 05:52.656
who I was.

05:52.700 --> 05:54.310
I saw the flyer that you made.

05:54.354 --> 05:56.312
- That was the best call
of my life.

05:56.356 --> 05:59.359
- What about the phone messages
you left your mom?

06:00.708 --> 06:02.057
- I don't know anything
about that.

06:02.100 --> 06:04.320
- You said the job
wasn't what you expected.

06:04.364 --> 06:05.669
You sounded scared.

06:05.713 --> 06:07.018
- Well, the doctors said

06:07.062 --> 06:08.672
that with a hit to the head
like that,

06:08.716 --> 06:11.458
it might take some time
for his memories--

06:11.501 --> 06:13.024
return.

06:13.068 --> 06:17.855
<i>♪</i>

06:17.899 --> 06:20.815
Look, Miss Lane,
we are so grateful

06:20.858 --> 06:23.992
for your help, but I'm just...

06:24.035 --> 06:25.820
so happy that he's back.

06:25.863 --> 06:28.736
All this other stuff,
it just doesn't matter anymore.

06:28.779 --> 06:31.478
- Sharon, someone tried
to kill you.

06:31.521 --> 06:33.175
- I have my son back.

06:33.218 --> 06:35.743
T--there's just no more
story to tell anymore.

06:35.786 --> 06:38.267
W--we just came
to say thank you.

06:38.310 --> 06:40.617
<i>♪</i>

06:40.661 --> 06:42.663
- It's up to you.
- What?

06:42.706 --> 06:44.447
You were almost murdered

06:44.491 --> 06:45.709
by someone
with superhuman strength,

06:45.753 --> 06:47.494
and you're just gonna
let that go?

06:47.537 --> 06:48.973
- You wanna write something?

06:49.017 --> 06:51.454
Write about how my missing son
has returned.

06:51.498 --> 06:53.021
That's a nice story.

06:54.065 --> 06:55.937
Thank you for your time.

07:02.334 --> 07:03.684
- Okay, that phony story

07:03.727 --> 07:05.947
was all sorts of rehearsed.
- I know.

07:05.990 --> 07:07.470
- Sharon almost got killed
by someone who works

07:07.514 --> 07:09.080
for Morgan Edge.
- Yep.

07:09.124 --> 07:10.778
- I'm acting like you
right now?

07:10.821 --> 07:13.607
- That's because we both know
this is a big story.

07:13.650 --> 07:15.086
And we will figure it out,
but for now,

07:15.130 --> 07:17.915
let's just be happy
she got her son back.

07:17.959 --> 07:22.137
<i>♪</i>

07:22.180 --> 07:24.531
<i>- It appears
we've successfully located</i>

07:24.574 --> 07:26.707
<i>Lois Lane, Captain Luthor.</i>

07:26.750 --> 07:29.927
<i>Are you certain this is
the best course of action?</i>

07:29.971 --> 07:31.189
- I am.

07:31.233 --> 07:33.409
One thing I know
for sure about this world...

07:33.453 --> 07:35.280
wherever Lois Lane goes,

07:35.324 --> 07:37.326
Superman follows.

07:37.369 --> 07:40.677
<i>♪</i>

07:44.246 --> 07:46.509
- Great, housewares.

07:46.553 --> 07:47.945
- All we could give
this year, Lana.

07:47.989 --> 07:50.687
- Oh, don't you apologize,
Aidy.

07:50.731 --> 07:53.124
Not after everything
you've been through.

07:53.168 --> 07:54.822
Thank you.

08:00.567 --> 08:01.742
- Hi, there.
- Hi.

08:01.785 --> 08:03.134
- Couple bags
of men's clothes.

08:03.178 --> 08:05.136
- Oh, great.
We always get so much

08:05.180 --> 08:07.574
women's clothes
but not enough men's.

08:07.617 --> 08:09.532
Can I get a name
for recognition?

08:09.576 --> 08:11.969
- Sure, it's Sharon
and Derek Powell.

08:14.276 --> 08:16.104
- Derek Powell?

08:16.147 --> 08:17.975
From New Carthage?

08:18.019 --> 08:19.803
Glad you're back. <i></i>

08:19.847 --> 08:21.675
- Yep, got a happy ending.

08:21.718 --> 08:24.242
- I-I'll go get
the rest of the bags.

08:27.594 --> 08:31.206
Ah.

08:36.864 --> 08:39.997
Ms. Larr,
there's something wrong.

08:41.564 --> 08:44.132
I--I don't know.
I--I feel off.

08:44.175 --> 08:45.525
Ah.

08:45.568 --> 08:47.483
<i>♪</i>

08:47.527 --> 08:49.180
I need to see you.

08:49.224 --> 08:50.530
Now.

08:50.573 --> 08:52.619
<i>- Hello?</i>

08:52.662 --> 08:55.317
<i>Are you there?
-</i>

08:55.360 --> 08:59.669
Ah!

09:04.282 --> 09:07.982
<i>♪</i>

09:13.727 --> 09:20.995
<i>♪</i>

09:22.910 --> 09:25.042
- Well, it's a different
look for you.

09:25.086 --> 09:27.349
- I feel like it really pops.

09:27.392 --> 09:29.046
- Ah.

09:29.090 --> 09:32.049
Yeah, it's definitely
assertive.

09:32.093 --> 09:35.575
You sure you want to wear that
to the Harvest Fest, honey?

09:35.618 --> 09:37.794
You know,
Lana's gonna be there.

09:37.838 --> 09:39.187
-
You're right.

09:39.230 --> 09:41.319
I should probably stick
with flannel.

09:42.843 --> 09:45.933
I know you don't like
talking about it, but...

09:46.847 --> 09:49.240
is Lana still seeing
that Cushing boy?

09:49.284 --> 09:50.633
- Mm.

09:50.677 --> 09:52.113
<i>- See?
No alarms.</i>

09:52.156 --> 09:53.680
<i>- Let's get out of here
as fast as we can.</i>

09:57.466 --> 09:58.989
- Easy, now!

09:59.033 --> 10:00.730
This is some real
high-end equipment.

10:00.774 --> 10:02.471
- Which you need
to put back.

10:03.385 --> 10:05.256
- I think you got
the wrong idea, here,

10:05.300 --> 10:06.649
Ski Mask Guy.

10:06.693 --> 10:08.346
- Pretty sure you used
that crowbar

10:08.390 --> 10:09.521
to break into this shop,

10:09.565 --> 10:10.958
where you stole 12 TVs,

10:11.001 --> 10:13.395
10 VCRs, and more than a few
salad shooters.

10:13.438 --> 10:14.657
<i>♪</i>

10:14.701 --> 10:16.311
Put the stuff back.

10:17.268 --> 10:18.661
- Sorry, kid.

10:18.705 --> 10:19.662
<i>♪</i>

10:27.191 --> 10:28.671
<i>♪</i>

10:30.542 --> 10:31.631
<i>♪</i>

10:31.674 --> 10:33.110
- Put it back.

10:33.154 --> 10:35.286
<i>♪</i>

10:35.330 --> 10:36.679
- Our bad.

10:36.723 --> 10:37.941
We'll put it all back.

10:37.985 --> 10:39.639
Like we were never here.

10:39.682 --> 10:44.905
<i>♪</i>

10:51.868 --> 10:53.653
- I need more hoses
on the roof now!

10:56.917 --> 10:59.789
- Tamara's gonna get you
looked at, okay?

10:59.833 --> 11:02.226
- Where's Mitch?
- Thought he was with you.

11:03.663 --> 11:04.794
- Mitch!

11:06.230 --> 11:07.362
Mitch!

11:08.015 --> 11:09.320
Mitch, you in here?

11:09.364 --> 11:10.539
<i>♪</i>

11:10.582 --> 11:12.672
-
- Mitch!

11:14.151 --> 11:15.457
Mitch!

11:15.500 --> 11:17.328
Mayday, Mayday, Mayday.
This is Chief Cushing.

11:17.372 --> 11:19.722
I got eyes on Mitch.
Bravo, Charlie, corner.

11:19.766 --> 11:21.071
Heavy smoke and fire.

11:21.115 --> 11:22.725
You're gonna be all right,
okay?

11:22.769 --> 11:24.379
Right, now, get your arm
around my shoulder.

11:24.422 --> 11:26.163
- Ah!
- There we go.

11:26.207 --> 11:27.687
- Ah.

11:30.428 --> 11:34.389
<i>♪</i>

11:34.432 --> 11:37.044
<i>- You're gonna be all right.
There you go.</i>

11:38.436 --> 11:40.003
Okay. Just come on.

11:40.047 --> 11:41.875
Let's pick up that pace
just a little bit, okay, bud?

11:44.399 --> 11:45.705
Ah!

11:49.491 --> 11:51.188
Ah, ah.

11:51.232 --> 11:55.149
<i>♪</i>

11:57.847 --> 11:59.501
- Close one, boss.

12:00.589 --> 12:01.590
Come on.

12:01.633 --> 12:02.765
- We got 'em, Chief.

12:02.809 --> 12:04.158
Come on, Mitch.

12:04.201 --> 12:05.550
- Come on.
- Here we go.

12:05.594 --> 12:07.161
Come on.
- Come on, let's just go.

12:07.204 --> 12:09.337
Come on!
-

12:09.380 --> 12:16.431
<i>♪</i>

12:17.867 --> 12:19.347
- Is that--

12:19.956 --> 12:21.958
is that frost?

12:22.002 --> 12:28.965
<i>♪</i>

12:29.009 --> 12:30.750
<i>- I should've been there
sooner.</i>

12:30.793 --> 12:32.012
By the time I got there,
all the donations

12:32.055 --> 12:33.404
were already destroyed.

12:33.448 --> 12:35.363
- That's awful.
What are they gonna do?

12:35.406 --> 12:36.364
- I don't know.

12:36.407 --> 12:37.539
Most people already gave

12:37.582 --> 12:39.149
everything they have to offer.

12:40.629 --> 12:43.414
Sharon Powell was hanging
around outside the Center.

12:43.458 --> 12:44.589
- At the fire?

12:44.633 --> 12:46.113
- Yeah.
- Was Derek there?

12:46.156 --> 12:47.984
- No. It seemed like she was
looking for someone, though.

12:48.028 --> 12:49.899
It could've been him.
- That doesn't sound right.

12:49.943 --> 12:52.249
I'm gonna go down
and start asking questions.

12:54.295 --> 12:55.775
- Guys, got your favorite
pizza.

12:55.818 --> 12:57.298
- I'm not hungry.

12:57.341 --> 12:59.604
- Eliza dumped him
this morning.

13:00.910 --> 13:03.260
- I'll go talk to him.

13:03.304 --> 13:05.480
<i>♪</i>

13:05.523 --> 13:07.525
- First breakups are rough.

13:07.569 --> 13:10.615
Pretty much crawled into
an REO Speedwagon rabbit hole.

13:10.659 --> 13:12.052
- Speedwagon?

13:12.095 --> 13:14.358
- Never mind.
- All right.

13:14.402 --> 13:16.578
<i>♪</i>

13:16.621 --> 13:17.753
- Jonathan?

13:17.797 --> 13:21.670
<i>♪</i>

13:21.713 --> 13:23.280
-
Jordan just had to go

13:23.324 --> 13:24.847
and announce it
to the world, huh?

13:24.891 --> 13:26.806
- He's just worried
about you.

13:27.415 --> 13:29.156
So am I.
Do you wanna talk about it?

13:29.199 --> 13:31.375
- What is there to talk about?
I mean, clearly,

13:31.419 --> 13:33.900
she knows that she can do
better than dating some kid

13:33.943 --> 13:35.597
from some
middle-of-nowhere town.

13:35.640 --> 13:37.904
- I'm sure it's complicated
for her, too, sweetie.

13:37.947 --> 13:39.906
Our move here
was really sudden.

13:39.949 --> 13:41.777
- Are you seriously
taking her side right now?

13:41.821 --> 13:43.648
- No.
I'm just saying,

13:43.692 --> 13:45.128
as a former
teenage girl myself,

13:45.172 --> 13:46.869
you gotta give it some time.

13:46.913 --> 13:48.740
She might wake up and remember

13:48.784 --> 13:50.481
how incredible you are.

13:50.525 --> 13:52.135
And if she doesn't,
then it's her loss.

13:52.179 --> 13:53.963
- Well, thanks for
your Cosmo Girl opinion,

13:54.007 --> 13:57.314
but, honestly, I just want
to be left alone right now.

13:57.358 --> 13:59.447
<i>♪</i>

14:07.020 --> 14:08.804
- Trigger warning, Lane.

14:08.848 --> 14:09.979
Don't want you
having any flashbacks

14:10.023 --> 14:11.633
to what happened to your car.

14:12.939 --> 14:15.202
- Any idea what caused this?

14:15.245 --> 14:16.551
- Not sure.

14:17.117 --> 14:19.336
You know, I don't know
what's more confusing,

14:19.380 --> 14:21.512
how the damn thing started
or how it ended.

14:21.556 --> 14:22.862
- Was anybody hurt?

14:24.385 --> 14:26.213
- Tom Mitchell.

14:26.256 --> 14:28.563
- I met him at your barbecue.
Nice guy.

14:29.390 --> 14:32.001
- He was the best man
at my wedding.

14:32.045 --> 14:34.134
You know, probably
the bravest person

14:34.177 --> 14:35.483
we got on this crew.

14:35.526 --> 14:37.354
- Is gonna be okay?

14:37.398 --> 14:39.139
- You know,
it's not looking good.

14:39.182 --> 14:41.706
So unless you got
any more questions--

14:41.750 --> 14:43.230
- I do have one, sorry.

14:43.273 --> 14:46.015
Have you seen this guy
anywhere near the Center?

14:46.059 --> 14:47.712
Derek Powell?

14:47.756 --> 14:49.497
- I might've seen him

14:49.540 --> 14:50.541
come around the back.

14:50.585 --> 14:51.978
W--why are you asking?

14:52.021 --> 14:54.545
- I need to talk to him
about a story.

14:54.589 --> 14:57.200
Thanks for your time.
I'm sorry about your friend.

15:00.682 --> 15:02.989
Chrissy, Kyle saw Derek Powell
at the Center

15:03.032 --> 15:04.555
as the fire trucks arrived.

15:04.599 --> 15:06.383
- Well, that's 50 shades
of suspicious.

15:06.427 --> 15:08.211
- We don't know anything
for sure yet.

15:08.255 --> 15:11.040
- My big reporter energy
knows something

15:11.084 --> 15:13.303
crazy weird's going on
with Derek Powell.

15:13.347 --> 15:14.652
- I need you to get his mom

15:14.696 --> 15:16.219
and get her to The Gazette
right now.

15:16.263 --> 15:18.047
<i>- On it.
- Miss Lane?</i>

15:18.091 --> 15:19.919
<i>♪</i>

15:19.962 --> 15:21.616
I've been looking for you.

15:21.659 --> 15:23.313
<i>♪</i>

15:26.316 --> 15:27.578
- So you're a reporter?

15:27.622 --> 15:28.579
- That's right.

15:28.623 --> 15:29.624
Marcus Bridgewater.

15:29.667 --> 15:30.886
- Sounds vaguely familiar.

15:30.930 --> 15:32.235
"Politico"?
- "Reuters."

15:32.279 --> 15:33.933
Mainly do business coverage,

15:33.976 --> 15:35.804
focusing on big tech.

15:35.847 --> 15:37.632
I have a background
in engineering.

15:37.675 --> 15:39.895
I used to work at LutherCorps.

15:39.939 --> 15:43.246
- Lex Luthor, the only human
being worse than Morgan Edge.

15:43.290 --> 15:44.900
- Guy, uh--

15:44.944 --> 15:46.380
Definitely has his secrets.

15:46.423 --> 15:48.599
- So what exactly brings
a "Reuters" tech reporter

15:48.643 --> 15:50.819
to Smallville, Kansas?

15:50.862 --> 15:52.429
- You.

15:52.473 --> 15:54.562
I'm a huge fan.
And after reading your piece

15:54.605 --> 15:56.433
on Morgan Edge--
- My heavily redacted piece.

15:56.477 --> 15:58.087
- I thought there might be
a bigger story here,

15:58.131 --> 16:00.002
so I did a little digging.

16:00.046 --> 16:02.613
- You trying to poach my story?
- That's not my intent.

16:02.657 --> 16:04.485
Just wanna be on team Lois.

16:04.528 --> 16:07.488
- Not sure I have much
of a roster these days.

16:08.532 --> 16:10.186
- Still have Superman.

16:10.230 --> 16:12.145
Unless someone else
is covering him

16:12.188 --> 16:13.711
now that you've left
Metropolis?

16:13.755 --> 16:15.800
- He's a public figure.
Anyone can cover him.

16:15.844 --> 16:17.106
- Yeah, but, you're the one

16:17.150 --> 16:19.587
who seems to always have
the inside track.

16:19.630 --> 16:21.197
- He's just someone
I report on.

16:21.241 --> 16:23.112
- Sure, but, without you,
I think we all know

16:23.156 --> 16:26.637
there'd be a lot more questions
about the guy.

16:28.161 --> 16:29.989
- So, what is it you have
on Morgan Edge?

16:30.032 --> 16:31.642
- Nothing yet.
But I think I may

16:31.686 --> 16:34.819
have found a way to get a look
inside the mines.

16:34.863 --> 16:35.995
- Thanks.

16:36.038 --> 16:37.474
Doesn't exactly sound legal.

16:37.518 --> 16:40.303
- The less you know,
the better.

16:40.347 --> 16:41.870
- Well, if you manage
to dig something up,

16:41.913 --> 16:43.176
give me a call.

16:43.219 --> 16:47.006
<i>♪</i>

16:47.049 --> 16:49.051
- Maybe we'll split
the byline?

16:49.095 --> 16:51.488
- Let's see what you come up
with first.

16:51.532 --> 16:52.750
<i>♪</i>

16:55.362 --> 16:58.060
- He really said that to you?

16:59.366 --> 17:01.324
Didn't even have the nerve.

17:01.368 --> 17:03.718
He sent me a text, I mean--

17:04.501 --> 17:06.764
I just got him back,
and--and out of nowhere,

17:06.808 --> 17:08.723
he needs "space"?

17:08.766 --> 17:11.552
- He say anything
about where he's going?

17:13.597 --> 17:15.817
Any chance I can see that text?

17:17.688 --> 17:19.212
- Sure.

17:21.083 --> 17:22.215
- You and Derek
wouldn't be sharing

17:22.258 --> 17:24.086
a phone plan, by any chance?

17:24.130 --> 17:25.566
- It's the only way
anyone can afford it

17:25.609 --> 17:27.089
these days.

17:27.133 --> 17:28.699
Why do you ask?

17:29.787 --> 17:31.093
- Um...

17:31.137 --> 17:33.008
I just wanted to vent.

17:33.052 --> 17:35.750
God, those phone companies
are such crooks, right?

17:38.753 --> 17:41.234
<i>♪</i>

17:44.019 --> 17:45.499
- Hey, Dad, um,

17:45.542 --> 17:48.154
mind if I leave early
to meet up with Sarah

17:48.197 --> 17:49.851
at Harvest Fest?

17:49.894 --> 17:51.548
- Uh...

17:51.592 --> 17:54.029
any chance this meetup
is, like, a--

17:54.073 --> 17:55.422
like a date?

17:55.465 --> 17:58.120
- I don't know.
Maybe.

17:58.164 --> 17:59.382
Yeah.
- Yeah?

17:59.426 --> 18:00.383
- Yes.
- Yeah?

18:00.427 --> 18:01.732
Yeah!

18:01.776 --> 18:03.386
- All right, all right.
- Okay, yes!

18:03.430 --> 18:04.822
Yes, of course you can!
- All right, Dad. Dad.

18:04.866 --> 18:06.215
- What, what?
This is what I was talking

18:06.259 --> 18:07.477
about, Harvest Festival.
- Be cool.

18:07.521 --> 18:08.565
- If I have to hear
anything else

18:08.609 --> 18:10.219
about this stupid Harvest Fest.

18:10.263 --> 18:13.831
- Jon.
- Farming or community or

18:13.875 --> 18:16.573
basically anything else
about this backwards-ass town.

18:16.617 --> 18:17.922
- Hey.

18:17.966 --> 18:20.490
I'm sorry about Eliza.

18:20.534 --> 18:22.275
- It's not about that, Dad.

18:22.318 --> 18:24.015
I wanna move back.

18:24.059 --> 18:25.713
I lost all my friends.

18:25.756 --> 18:27.410
I'm probably never gonna play
football again,

18:27.454 --> 18:29.151
and--and now, what?
You just expect me

18:29.195 --> 18:30.935
to drop my life
for everyone else's?

18:30.979 --> 18:32.589
- Look, I know, I know.
A lot has changed.

18:32.633 --> 18:34.374
But I promise you,
it's all gonna work out.

18:34.417 --> 18:35.679
-
You don't know that!

18:35.723 --> 18:36.550
- I get it.

18:36.593 --> 18:37.768
There was a time in my life

18:37.812 --> 18:39.161
when I felt just like you.

18:39.205 --> 18:40.249
- Yeah, well, I'm sure.
When was that?

18:40.293 --> 18:41.772
When you were, I don't know,

18:41.816 --> 18:43.122
lifting an oil tanker

18:43.165 --> 18:44.949
or maybe flying laps
around Saturn?

18:44.993 --> 18:46.255
- Jonathan--
- No, Dad!

18:46.299 --> 18:48.083
I'm not like you,
and I'm not like Superboy

18:48.127 --> 18:49.171
over there, okay?

18:49.215 --> 18:50.607
And this town?

18:50.651 --> 18:53.915
It is my kryptonite.
I hate it.

18:56.961 --> 19:00.704
<i>♪</i>

19:00.748 --> 19:03.142
Look, Dad, um...

19:03.185 --> 19:06.623
Bryan Kelso's older brother
has a place, okay?

19:06.667 --> 19:09.148
He just graduated from Met U,
there's a spare bedroom.

19:09.191 --> 19:10.758
It's just outside of downtown.

19:10.801 --> 19:12.063
I--I was thinking,

19:12.107 --> 19:13.674
maybe I could just
stay with them.

19:13.717 --> 19:14.892
- Uh, no, no.

19:14.936 --> 19:16.590
You are not going to stay
with the Kelsos.

19:16.633 --> 19:18.157
- You know what?
Maybe I'll just do it

19:18.200 --> 19:19.810
anyways, then,
because that's what Jordan did

19:19.854 --> 19:23.118
with football, and you let him
get away with it.

19:23.162 --> 19:25.164
Whatever.
Jordan, come on.

19:25.207 --> 19:26.295
If this Harvest Fest
is so awesome,

19:26.339 --> 19:28.079
let's go have some real fun.

19:28.123 --> 19:29.690
<i>♪</i>

19:29.733 --> 19:30.908
- Go.

19:30.952 --> 19:32.171
- Thanks.

19:32.214 --> 19:33.476
<i>♪</i>

19:33.520 --> 19:35.174
<i>- Will you listen to me?</i>

19:35.217 --> 19:37.828
We've talked about this, Clark.

19:37.872 --> 19:40.875
You can't be running around
playing masked vigilante.

19:40.918 --> 19:43.225
- They were stealing!
- I understand that,

19:43.269 --> 19:46.097
but we've got rules
in this family.

19:46.141 --> 19:47.534
- Those were Dad's rules,

19:47.577 --> 19:49.144
and he's not here anymore.

19:49.188 --> 19:50.841
- That doesn't mean
you get to ignore

19:50.885 --> 19:52.234
everything he taught you.

19:52.278 --> 19:53.844
- It's been a year.
You know?

19:53.888 --> 19:56.151
We can't keep pretending
everything's the same.

19:56.195 --> 19:58.371
We have to move on
with our lives.

19:58.414 --> 20:00.808
- Moving on
can be a distraction.

20:00.851 --> 20:02.679
Sometimes to heal,
you've gotta--

20:02.723 --> 20:04.725
you've gotta sit
with the feeling, you know?

20:04.768 --> 20:07.206
Let it run its course.
- Dad understood.

20:07.249 --> 20:09.686
He knew I was sent here
for a reason.

20:09.730 --> 20:11.601
- Your father and I both knew

20:11.645 --> 20:13.603
you were sent here
for a reason.

20:13.647 --> 20:14.735
- Well, I'm pretty sure
that reason

20:14.778 --> 20:17.346
wasn't to be Martha Kent's son.

20:19.000 --> 20:22.569
<i>♪</i>

20:22.612 --> 20:24.266
- Thank you
for all your hard work.

20:24.310 --> 20:26.137
Clark is gonna be so surprised.

20:26.181 --> 20:27.530
Okay, I'll see you soon.
-

20:27.574 --> 20:29.271
I'm sorry I'm late, babe.

20:29.315 --> 20:31.230
- It's okay.
How's Mitch?

20:31.273 --> 20:34.233
- Well, he--he took in
a lot of smoke.

20:34.276 --> 20:36.496
Doc's a little worried
that the lung damage

20:36.539 --> 20:39.325
might be permanent.
- Oh, God.

20:39.368 --> 20:41.065
- Yeah, it's--it's
a lot questions

20:41.109 --> 20:42.676
as to whether or not

20:42.719 --> 20:45.287
he's gonna be able
to come back to the station.

20:45.331 --> 20:47.028
- I'm sorry.

20:48.072 --> 20:49.770
Aww.

20:51.467 --> 20:52.990
Have you been drinking?

20:53.034 --> 20:55.384
- Y--yeah, you know,
me and Tamara and the boys,

20:55.428 --> 20:58.387
I mean, we went out and had
a drink in his honor.

20:58.431 --> 21:01.303
- Smells like you had
a little more than one.

21:01.347 --> 21:03.479
- L--let me just
get a quick bite,

21:03.523 --> 21:06.569
get showered up--
- I have people waiting on me.

21:06.613 --> 21:08.005
We're trying to figure out
what to do

21:08.049 --> 21:09.398
about the donations we lost.
- Come on, babe.

21:09.442 --> 21:11.400
It's been a long, hard day.

21:11.444 --> 21:12.575
Okay?
Just--

21:12.619 --> 21:13.924
it'll only take a minute.

21:13.968 --> 21:15.535
- Mom?

21:16.449 --> 21:18.277
Just take Soph.

21:19.974 --> 21:22.498
- Let me just--
- No, I got it.

21:22.542 --> 21:24.631
Thank you.
- Mm-hmm.

21:43.824 --> 21:46.130
- I really hope she's not
having second thoughts.

21:46.174 --> 21:48.132
- Jordan, she's the one
who asked you, man.

21:48.176 --> 21:50.526
Just have a--have a shred
of confidence, okay?

21:50.570 --> 21:52.136
- Hey, look.
It's the Kent sisters.

21:52.180 --> 21:53.834
- Yo.

21:53.877 --> 21:55.618
What's up, boys?
- Got your text, QB2.

21:55.662 --> 21:57.141
We are locked and loaded.

21:57.185 --> 21:58.404
- Hell, yeah.
- Better drink up

21:58.447 --> 22:00.014
before the big game.

22:01.189 --> 22:03.670
- Are you sure that's
a good idea tonight?

22:03.713 --> 22:05.367
- Uh--

22:05.411 --> 22:07.804
Thanks for looking out, Mom.

22:07.848 --> 22:09.023
Mm.

22:12.679 --> 22:14.811
Why don't you go find Sarah?
- Fine.

22:14.855 --> 22:17.379
You do you, party guy.
We'll see how that goes.

22:17.423 --> 22:18.511
- We'll see.

22:18.554 --> 22:19.903
-
Okay, we will.

22:19.947 --> 22:21.165
- Yeah.

22:29.696 --> 22:31.350
- Dad?

22:31.393 --> 22:33.047
- Hey.
Thanks.

22:34.831 --> 22:37.747
Hey, you, sit--sit down
for just a minute.

22:43.927 --> 22:45.407
Hey, you remember that song
I used to sing you

22:45.451 --> 22:46.887
when you were a little girl?

22:47.714 --> 22:51.457
♪ De la Sierra Morena

22:51.500 --> 22:56.766
♪ Cielito lindo,
vienen bajando ♪

22:56.810 --> 23:00.727
♪ Un par de ojitos negros

23:00.770 --> 23:03.120
♪ Cielito lindo,
de contrabando ♪

23:03.164 --> 23:04.339
- Dad, stop!

23:07.560 --> 23:09.910
That was a long time ago.

23:10.780 --> 23:13.479
- Yeah, time really does fly,
doesn't it?

23:15.176 --> 23:16.395
- I should get going.

23:16.438 --> 23:18.745
-
Yeah.

23:19.659 --> 23:22.096
Yeah, I'll be--I'll be right
behind you, <i>mi hijita.</i>

23:23.402 --> 23:24.925
- Yeah.

23:24.968 --> 23:28.581
<i>♪</i>

23:34.935 --> 23:39.418
<i>♪</i>

23:39.461 --> 23:40.636
- I started that fire.

23:40.680 --> 23:42.333
If he finds out it was me--

23:42.377 --> 23:44.248
- Nothing is going
to happen to you.

23:44.292 --> 23:46.294
This was an accident.

23:46.337 --> 23:47.469
- But if I can't control it--

23:47.513 --> 23:49.819
- We can fix this.

23:49.863 --> 23:51.168
Follow me.

23:51.212 --> 23:58.437
<i>♪</i>

24:01.440 --> 24:02.789
- Gotcha.

24:09.491 --> 24:12.625
<i>♪</i>

24:22.286 --> 24:28.292
<i>♪</i>

24:31.382 --> 24:33.472
- I'm sorry about earlier,
Clark.

24:33.515 --> 24:35.038
- It's okay, Mom.
I shouldn't have gotten

24:35.082 --> 24:36.518
so upset, and you were right--

24:36.562 --> 24:38.999
- No, no, just listen to me.

24:39.042 --> 24:40.957
I didn't want to admit that

24:41.001 --> 24:45.222
this home isn't the best place
for you anymore.

24:45.266 --> 24:46.572
You are special,

24:46.615 --> 24:50.619
and I know you're meant
for--for bigger things.

24:50.663 --> 24:53.535
And that time might have come.

24:53.579 --> 24:54.623
- What is this?

24:54.667 --> 24:55.929
- Your father found it

24:55.972 --> 24:57.496
in the pod when you arrived.

24:57.539 --> 24:58.584
I don't know what it does

24:58.627 --> 25:00.150
or what it's for, I just--

25:00.194 --> 25:02.805
I just know it belongs to you.

25:02.849 --> 25:06.505
And it might be the key
to figuring out

25:06.548 --> 25:08.463
what your future is.

25:08.507 --> 25:11.379
<i>♪</i>

25:12.859 --> 25:15.644
<i>♪</i>

25:18.821 --> 25:20.780
- Hey, hey, Lana.
How are you?

25:20.823 --> 25:21.911
- Hey, Cobb.
- How are you?

25:21.955 --> 25:23.260
- I'm good.

25:23.304 --> 25:24.523
- I, uh--

25:24.566 --> 25:26.263
I heard about Mitch.

25:26.307 --> 25:28.309
It's a damn shame.
- Yeah.

25:28.352 --> 25:29.702
- Listen, um--

25:29.745 --> 25:31.181
is Kyle gonna be here
tonight, or--

25:31.225 --> 25:33.749
- Oh, he--he wanted
to stay at the hospital.

25:33.793 --> 25:35.446
- He's a good man, that Kyle.

25:35.490 --> 25:37.361
- He is.

25:44.107 --> 25:45.195
- Hey.
- Hey!

25:45.239 --> 25:47.850
I'm really sorry I'm late.

25:47.894 --> 25:49.635
- It's all right.
You okay?

25:49.678 --> 25:51.158
- No, not really.

25:52.028 --> 25:54.422
Um, but, I don't really
wanna do

25:54.465 --> 25:56.598
sad stories tonight, so.

25:56.642 --> 25:58.339
- All right.

25:58.382 --> 26:00.210
My dad can't shut up
about these.

26:00.254 --> 26:01.647
-
You probably shouldn't eat

26:01.690 --> 26:04.040
anything here
that's on a stick.

26:04.084 --> 26:06.347
Come on, let me buy you
some elephant ears.

26:07.783 --> 26:08.741
- All right.

26:08.784 --> 26:10.046
Yeah.
- Yeah?

26:10.090 --> 26:11.221
- Yeah, that sounds great.
- Okay.

26:16.705 --> 26:23.407
<i>♪</i>

26:28.195 --> 26:30.327
- What makes you think this
time, it'll be any different?

26:30.371 --> 26:31.633
- Trust me.

26:31.677 --> 26:35.855
<i>♪</i>

26:38.466 --> 26:45.473
<i>♪</i>

26:52.872 --> 26:54.482
<i>♪</i>

26:54.525 --> 26:56.005
- You know, I think I'm
starting to see what my dad

26:56.049 --> 26:58.225
saw in this place.

26:58.268 --> 27:00.662
- From this?
Really?

27:00.706 --> 27:02.011
<i>♪</i>

27:02.055 --> 27:03.926
- It's pretty great.

27:03.970 --> 27:08.931
<i>♪</i>

27:08.975 --> 27:10.585
- Look,

27:10.629 --> 27:13.153
about earlier...

27:14.023 --> 27:16.112
everything's not okay.

27:16.156 --> 27:18.375
<i>♪</i>

27:18.419 --> 27:19.899
It's just--

27:19.942 --> 27:21.683
I don't know, the sheer weight

27:21.727 --> 27:24.468
of all of the really bad things
that are going on in my life,

27:24.512 --> 27:26.949
and I'm pretty sure
that my therapist is tired of

27:26.993 --> 27:28.821
hearing me talk
about the same stuff.

27:28.864 --> 27:30.605
<i>♪</i>

27:30.649 --> 27:32.302
- So, try me.

27:32.346 --> 27:33.956
- Well--

27:34.000 --> 27:35.479
okay.
My dad, he--

27:35.523 --> 27:37.481
- Yo, yo, guys, look!
It's everybody's favorite

27:37.525 --> 27:40.136
Kent brother.
It's Mr. Charming, baby!

27:40.180 --> 27:41.572
Look at this guy.
- Hey, hey, hey.

27:41.616 --> 27:43.226
Not now, all right?
Not now, please.

27:43.270 --> 27:44.532
- Whoa, whoa, relax, relax,
relax, relax.

27:44.575 --> 27:45.925
Chill, chill, chill, chill.
Look.

27:45.968 --> 27:47.796
Guys, guys, guys.
Get this.

27:47.840 --> 27:49.972
It's this guy's
first date ever.

27:50.016 --> 27:51.104
It's his first date!

27:51.147 --> 27:52.105
-
- What?

27:52.148 --> 27:54.020
- First-timer.

27:56.152 --> 27:57.980
- Wow.
You can't go one weekend

27:58.024 --> 27:59.590
without partying like idiots?

27:59.634 --> 28:01.027
It's kind of pathetic.

28:01.070 --> 28:02.768
- Sarah, hey, look, you need--
- Don't touch me!

28:02.811 --> 28:05.292
- Hey, we're just kidding.
- Don't talk to me like that!

28:05.335 --> 28:07.250
- Look, uh, he's--he's having

28:07.294 --> 28:08.991
a really rough day,
that's all this is, okay?

28:09.035 --> 28:10.427
- Oh, you're having
a rough day?

28:10.471 --> 28:12.560
You have no idea
what real problems are like.

28:12.603 --> 28:14.605
For people who don't come
from a picture-perfect family

28:14.649 --> 28:16.129
like you,

28:16.172 --> 28:18.131
you all can just get drunk
and act like total idiots

28:18.174 --> 28:20.829
and think that there's never
any consequences?

28:20.873 --> 28:22.091
- Yo, Sarah,

28:22.135 --> 28:23.527
we were just--we
were just kidding.

28:23.571 --> 28:24.354
I'm--I'm sorry.

28:24.398 --> 28:25.486
- Save it.
Have fun.

28:25.529 --> 28:27.706
Talk to you later.
Move!

28:28.358 --> 28:29.577
- Wait, Sarah--
- Jordan.

28:29.620 --> 28:31.622
Hey, Jordan!
- What, what, what?

28:31.666 --> 28:32.928
- Jordan.

28:32.972 --> 28:35.539
Look, I'm--I'm sorry, man.
I didn't--

28:35.583 --> 28:38.717
I didn't mean to ruin
your night like that.

28:38.760 --> 28:40.806
I'm sorry.

28:42.808 --> 28:44.505
- It's all right.

28:44.548 --> 28:45.767
Let's just--

28:45.811 --> 28:47.247
let's just get you some water.

28:47.290 --> 28:48.857
Okay?
- Okay.

28:48.901 --> 28:49.945
I'm sorry.

28:49.989 --> 28:55.516
<i>♪</i>

28:55.559 --> 28:57.692
- You're right.
These are severely underrated.

28:57.736 --> 28:59.912
- Right?
- Yes.

28:59.955 --> 29:01.783
You talk to Jonathan?
- Whoa!

29:01.827 --> 29:03.089
Um, yeah.

29:03.132 --> 29:05.569
He wants to move
back to Metropolis.

29:05.613 --> 29:06.701
- He said that?

29:06.745 --> 29:08.181
- Yeah, among other things.

29:08.224 --> 29:10.531
-
Here he comes.

29:11.271 --> 29:13.839
- Oh, and he's been drinking.

29:13.882 --> 29:15.318
- What?

29:15.362 --> 29:17.059
You've been drinking?

29:17.103 --> 29:18.582
- What?
- Your dad can smell it.

29:18.626 --> 29:20.541
I can smell it.
The whole town can smell it.

29:20.584 --> 29:22.064
- It's--it's not
that big a deal.

29:22.108 --> 29:23.936
- Excuse me?
- Okay, both of you,

29:23.979 --> 29:26.329
call a rideshare
and go home right now.

29:26.373 --> 29:28.201
- Yes, ma'am.
- Fine, we were going anyway.

29:28.244 --> 29:29.202
- Go faster!

29:30.507 --> 29:32.074
Chrissy, now is not
a good time.

29:32.118 --> 29:34.511
- Okay, so, Sharon Powell
came into the office

29:34.555 --> 29:37.253
and I, like, totally sleuthed
my way onto her phone

29:37.297 --> 29:39.168
to get Derek's location.

29:39.212 --> 29:41.344
So then I thought, "WWLLD,"

29:41.388 --> 29:42.781
<i>"what would Lois Lane do,"
which is easy,</i>

29:42.824 --> 29:44.086
<i>dig deeper
and follow the lead,</i>

29:44.130 --> 29:45.740
<i>only I never would've thought</i>

29:45.784 --> 29:48.569
it would lead me to him
making out with Leslie Larr.

29:48.612 --> 29:51.180
- Leslie Larr is there
with Derek Powell?

29:51.224 --> 29:53.487
- Yeah, she took him
to this building

29:53.530 --> 29:56.142
where there's this crazy
Bride of Frankenstein machine.

30:05.586 --> 30:07.153
- Did it work?

30:13.246 --> 30:16.553
<i>♪</i>

30:24.126 --> 30:25.475
- What is this?

30:25.519 --> 30:27.434
-
Protect the asset.

30:30.350 --> 30:36.704
<i>♪</i>

30:36.747 --> 30:38.967
<i>- Projectile in motion, sir.</i>

30:39.011 --> 30:40.839
<i>Speed and flight pattern
unique</i>

30:40.882 --> 30:43.015
<i>to Kryptonian air mobiles.</i>

30:43.058 --> 30:44.886
- Kal-El's here?

30:44.930 --> 30:48.368
<i>♪</i>

30:51.414 --> 30:58.682
<i>♪</i>

31:02.512 --> 31:09.737
<i>♪</i>

31:16.396 --> 31:19.442
<i>♪</i>

31:22.489 --> 31:25.187
<i>♪</i>

31:29.931 --> 31:31.890
- They're two of them? <i>
- It appears so,</i>

31:31.933 --> 31:34.196
<i>though I have still yet
to identify the other.</i>

31:34.240 --> 31:36.416
- Where'd they go? <i>
- Flight algorithm suggests</i>

31:36.459 --> 31:38.026
<i>a five-mile circumference.</i>

31:38.070 --> 31:40.637
<i>Continue on this road,
and we'll intersect</i>

31:40.681 --> 31:42.204
<i>in 23 seconds.</i>

31:42.248 --> 31:43.379
- Take over.

31:43.423 --> 31:45.207
<i>- Auto-drive engaged.</i>

31:45.251 --> 31:52.475
<i>♪</i>

31:58.307 --> 31:59.439
- What did she do to you?

31:59.482 --> 32:02.137
- She resurrected me, Kal-El.

32:02.181 --> 32:04.009
You're not alone anymore.

32:13.018 --> 32:20.068
<i>♪</i>

32:28.555 --> 32:30.426
<i>- 45 degrees southeast,</i>

32:30.470 --> 32:33.429
<i>in three, two, one.</i>

32:33.473 --> 32:35.388
<i>Fire.</i>

32:35.431 --> 32:38.608
<i>♪</i>

32:48.140 --> 32:54.233
<i>♪</i>

32:54.276 --> 32:56.104
- I can help you.

32:56.148 --> 32:59.238
- No, you can't.

32:59.281 --> 33:01.588
I'm already dead.

33:04.025 --> 33:05.374
Ah!

33:05.418 --> 33:07.028
- No!
Wait, wait, wait!

33:07.072 --> 33:14.122
<i>♪</i>

33:33.402 --> 33:35.448
- I guess Harvest Fest
was kind of a bust, huh?

33:38.103 --> 33:39.539
- Hey.

33:40.627 --> 33:43.369
I just wanted to say that...

33:44.631 --> 33:46.154
I'm--I'm really sorry

33:46.198 --> 33:48.722
and I promise that--
- Stop.

33:50.115 --> 33:51.333
It's okay.

33:51.377 --> 33:54.510
This is your one
"get out of jail free" card.

33:54.554 --> 33:55.685
- It is?

33:55.729 --> 33:56.686
- Wait, seriously?

33:56.730 --> 33:57.861
- Jonathan, I told you,

33:57.905 --> 34:00.168
I know how you feel, and I do.

34:00.212 --> 34:01.778
When I was just a couple years
older than you,

34:01.822 --> 34:03.345
I did leave home.

34:04.520 --> 34:06.087
- Why?
- Lots of reasons.

34:06.131 --> 34:09.090
The main one was that I needed
to become someone else.

34:09.134 --> 34:12.006
Someone I thought was more
important than Clark Kent.

34:12.050 --> 34:14.704
And to do that,
I had to leave Smallville.

34:14.748 --> 34:16.054
- And he never came back.

34:16.097 --> 34:17.881
- I still think
about that decision.

34:17.925 --> 34:19.231
That time that I gave up

34:19.274 --> 34:20.884
with my mom,
I never got it back.

34:20.928 --> 34:23.409
She only had
so much time to give,

34:23.452 --> 34:25.715
and she sacrificed it for me.

34:26.716 --> 34:28.849
Jonathan,
you have your own path.

34:28.892 --> 34:30.198
And it might not feel like it
right now,

34:30.242 --> 34:32.374
but I know it's gonna lead
to great things.

34:32.418 --> 34:35.812
All I'm asking is that you give
Smallville a little more time.

34:35.856 --> 34:38.206
If, after that, things
still aren't working out,

34:38.250 --> 34:40.643
then we can discuss
other options.

34:42.515 --> 34:44.734
- Okay.
- Okay.

34:44.778 --> 34:46.780
Right, I wanna
give you something.

34:47.781 --> 34:49.870
Something from that time
in my life.

34:52.916 --> 34:57.138
<i>♪</i>

34:57.182 --> 34:58.748
- Dad, there's nothing
in here.

34:58.792 --> 35:00.359
- The box is the gift.

35:00.402 --> 35:02.752
Your granddad gave that
to my mom when he proposed.

35:02.796 --> 35:04.711
And she gave it to me

35:04.754 --> 35:06.669
when it was my time to leave.

35:06.713 --> 35:08.193
- Wow.

35:08.236 --> 35:09.716
<i>♪</i>

35:09.759 --> 35:11.370
- All right, it's getting late,
you better go upstairs

35:11.413 --> 35:14.112
before we change our minds
about that punishment.

35:14.938 --> 35:16.462
- Thanks, Dad.

35:16.505 --> 35:18.420
<i>♪</i>

35:18.464 --> 35:19.987
- See ya.

35:22.511 --> 35:24.078
- Softy.

35:25.079 --> 35:26.428
- I know.

35:30.519 --> 35:32.782
<i>♪</i>

35:32.826 --> 35:36.308
- I'm still trying to process
what happened to Derek Powell.

35:36.351 --> 35:37.961
<i>♪</i>

35:38.005 --> 35:40.660
I feel so bad for his mom.

35:40.703 --> 35:43.271
<i>♪</i>

35:43.315 --> 35:46.318
Can't believe he just
killed himself like that.

35:47.188 --> 35:48.842
- I don't think
it was Derek.

35:48.885 --> 35:50.844
- It was his body.
- Yeah, but his powers

35:50.887 --> 35:53.107
were erratic, like Tag Harris.

35:53.151 --> 35:55.892
And he said he'd been
resurrected...

35:55.936 --> 35:57.285
whatever that means.

35:57.329 --> 35:59.157
- Well, whatever Edge
and Leslie are doing

35:59.200 --> 36:01.811
with that machine, it has
something to do with the mines.

36:01.855 --> 36:06.729
<i>♪</i>

36:10.255 --> 36:11.343
- Hey.

36:11.386 --> 36:12.518
- Hi.

36:12.561 --> 36:13.823
- I know it isn't much,

36:13.867 --> 36:15.216
but every little bit helps,
right?

36:15.260 --> 36:17.871
- Aw, thank you.
That's so thoughtful.

36:17.914 --> 36:19.177
- Just wish that we could
replace everything

36:19.220 --> 36:20.874
that was lost in the fire.

36:20.917 --> 36:23.050
- Oh, you're never
gonna believe this.

36:23.093 --> 36:25.400
We already have.
- What?

36:25.444 --> 36:27.576
How?
- Morgan Edge.

36:27.620 --> 36:29.099
He heard about what happened

36:29.143 --> 36:31.667
and wrote a check
to replace everything,

36:31.711 --> 36:32.886
and then some.

36:32.929 --> 36:34.279
- Very generous.

36:34.322 --> 36:37.586
- I--I guess he just
wanted to help.

36:39.371 --> 36:41.068
Okay, come with me.

36:41.111 --> 36:43.853
One last donation
you need to see.

36:46.465 --> 36:47.770
- Okay?
-

36:47.814 --> 36:50.817
<i>♪</i>

36:50.860 --> 36:52.166
<i>- As you know,</i>

36:52.210 --> 36:54.037
the Harvest Festival
was your mom's

36:54.081 --> 36:55.778
favorite time of the year,

36:55.822 --> 36:58.172
and we really feel her absence.

36:58.216 --> 37:02.307
Martha Kent was everything
this town aspires to be.

37:02.350 --> 37:03.873
She was kind,

37:03.917 --> 37:05.266
she was generous,

37:05.310 --> 37:08.443
and she was always there
when you needed her.

37:08.487 --> 37:10.706
Everyone in Smallville

37:10.750 --> 37:13.056
can remember her
sitting right here,

37:13.100 --> 37:15.145
talking with and laughing with

37:15.189 --> 37:17.409
whoever was right there
beside her.

37:17.452 --> 37:20.412
And though she is no longer
physically with us,

37:20.455 --> 37:23.893
her spirit remains,
and she will be

37:23.937 --> 37:26.635
right here
for whoever needs her.

37:32.772 --> 37:35.078
- Did you know about this?

37:35.122 --> 37:36.471
- Are you gonna sit down?

37:38.473 --> 37:45.524
<i>♪</i>

37:51.051 --> 37:53.967
- The train will be here
any minute.

37:54.750 --> 37:55.882
Clark?

37:59.799 --> 38:01.975
It's time, Clark.

38:06.588 --> 38:08.155
<i>♪</i>

38:11.376 --> 38:18.426
<i>♪</i>

38:24.824 --> 38:27.827
<i>♪</i>

38:27.870 --> 38:30.177
- I was so selfish.

38:30.220 --> 38:31.787
- Everybody is at that age.

38:31.831 --> 38:33.615
It's part of growing up.

38:33.659 --> 38:35.791
- Yeah, but Mom knew that.

38:35.835 --> 38:37.837
And she let me go anyway.

38:37.880 --> 38:41.057
- Because she loved you
and she wanted you to be happy.

38:42.145 --> 38:44.322
- And now we're
at the point where

38:44.365 --> 38:46.846
our own kids are talking
about leaving home.

38:46.889 --> 38:48.500
It feels like they
were just born.

38:48.543 --> 38:50.545
- It's easy for you to say,
you didn't have to go

38:50.589 --> 38:52.373
through 27 hours of labor.

38:52.417 --> 38:54.114
- That's true.

38:55.855 --> 39:00.860
<i>♪</i>

39:00.903 --> 39:02.557
- Love you.

39:02.601 --> 39:04.211
- Love you too.

39:08.041 --> 39:15.004
<i>♪</i>

39:17.224 --> 39:19.313
- <i>
- Biometric readings</i>

39:19.357 --> 39:21.794
<i>suggests your pulse
is abnormally high.</i>

39:21.837 --> 39:23.273
- <i>
- This must be</i>

39:23.317 --> 39:25.319
<i>about Lois Lane.
- Hmm.</i>

39:25.363 --> 39:27.843
<i>- It is worth reminding you
that this is not</i>

39:27.887 --> 39:29.845
<i>the Lois Lane from your world.</i>

39:29.889 --> 39:32.282
- Everything about her
is the same.

39:33.458 --> 39:36.069
Everything, except she marries
someone else.

39:36.112 --> 39:37.505
- Come back to me.

39:37.549 --> 39:38.680
- I always do.

39:38.724 --> 39:41.291
<i>♪</i>

39:41.335 --> 39:44.033
<i>- There are other variables
that you have not t--</i>

39:45.774 --> 39:49.387
<i>♪</i>

39:50.649 --> 39:54.392
- I'm glad that Jon
didn't get into trouble.

39:54.435 --> 39:56.045
- Yeah.

39:56.089 --> 39:59.397
Uh, my dad was pretty cool
about it, it was nice.

40:01.486 --> 40:03.575
- Can you tell Jon
that I'm sorry?

40:03.618 --> 40:07.100
I didn't--I didn't mean
to get so mad at him.

40:07.143 --> 40:09.058
- It's no big deal.

40:09.102 --> 40:11.060
- It kind of is, though.

40:15.369 --> 40:17.327
I know that I asked you
out on the date,

40:17.371 --> 40:20.156
only to completely
and totally ruin it, but,

40:20.200 --> 40:23.856
I think I could really just
use a friend

40:23.899 --> 40:25.771
more than anything else.

40:27.120 --> 40:28.513
- Yeah.

40:29.601 --> 40:32.299
Yeah, um...

40:32.342 --> 40:36.303
well, as long as we still get
to spend some time together.

40:36.346 --> 40:39.567
- Yeah, I do believe that
that's what friends do.

40:39.611 --> 40:41.308
So...

40:41.351 --> 40:43.005
- You know, you were the one
that ruined the date.

40:43.049 --> 40:44.398
- Hey!
So now you don't

40:44.442 --> 40:46.922
want to be friends?
- Eh, you know...

40:46.966 --> 40:49.751
I'll think about it.
-

40:49.795 --> 40:51.318
-
- Mm-kay.

40:52.275 --> 40:59.457
<i>♪</i>

41:06.681 --> 41:07.987
Tag?

41:08.640 --> 41:10.903
- What did you do to me?
- What?

41:14.384 --> 41:15.429
Tell me!
- Hey, man.

41:15.473 --> 41:16.735
Wait, wait, wait, wait.

41:16.778 --> 41:18.301
<i>♪</i>

41:21.566 --> 41:25.178
<i>♪</i>
